## 3. Adding a New Module — Step-by-Step

This example uses `product` as the module name. Replace with your own.

### Step 1 — Create the module's Rust file with DB init

Create a new file at
[src-tauri/src/api/product.rs](file:///e:/ruixinglong/tauri-kits/src-tauri/src/api/)
(one file per module — do NOT append to `api.rs`).

The module file owns:
- its table DDL (in an `api_<module>_init` command),
- its struct,
- its CRUD commands.

```rust
// src-tauri/src/api/product.rs
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};
use sqlx::Row;
use tauri::AppHandle;

use super::{ApiResponse, PageResponse, get_db_pool};

#[derive(Debug, Serialize, Deserialize)]
pub struct Product {
    pub id: Option<i64>,
    pub name: String,
    pub price: f64,
    pub state: i32,
    pub create_time: Option<String>,
    pub update_time: Option<String>,
}

#[tauri::command]
pub async fn api_product_init(app_handle: AppHandle) -> ApiResponse<String> {
    match get_db_pool(&app_handle).await {
        Ok(pool) => {
            let sql = r#"
                CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS product (
                    id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
                    name TEXT NOT NULL,
                    price REAL NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,
                    state INTEGER DEFAULT 1,
                    create_time TEXT,
                    update_time TEXT
                );
            "#;
            match sqlx::query(sql).execute(&pool).await {
                Ok(_) => ApiResponse::success("product table ready".to_string()),
                Err(e) => ApiResponse::error(500, &format!("Failed to create table: {}", e)),
            }
        }
        Err(e) => ApiResponse::error(500, &format!("Failed to connect to database: {}", e)),
    }
}
```

Rules:

- Always `CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS`.
- Include `id`, `create_time`, `update_time` for consistency.
- Use `TEXT` for timestamps (formatted as `YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS` via `chrono`).
- Each module owns its own `api_<module>_init` command — never inline DDL
  into the shared `api_db_init`.

### Step 2 — Add CRUD commands in the same module file

Continue in
[src-tauri/src/api/product.rs](file:///e:/ruixinglong/tauri-kits/src-tauri/src/api/)
with the CRUD commands:

```rust
#[tauri::command]
pub async fn api_product_list(
    page: i64,
    page_size: i64,
    app_handle: AppHandle,
) -> ApiResponse<PageResponse<Product>> {
    // Mirror api_user_list: COUNT + SELECT LIMIT/OFFSET
}

#[tauri::command]
pub async fn api_product_get(id: i64, app_handle: AppHandle) -> ApiResponse<Product> { ... }

#[tauri::command]
pub async fn api_product_create(product: Product, app_handle: AppHandle) -> ApiResponse<i64> { ... }

#[tauri::command]
pub async fn api_product_update(id: i64, product: Product, app_handle: AppHandle) -> ApiResponse<i64> { ... }

#[tauri::command]
pub async fn api_product_delete(id: i64, app_handle: AppHandle) -> ApiResponse<i64> { ... }
```

Conventions:

- Reuse `get_db_pool(&app_handle).await` (re-exported from `api.rs` via
  `use super::...`) for the SQLite connection.
- Hash passwords with `Md5`; do NOT return the password hash to the frontend
  (set `password: "".to_string()` in the response struct).
- Format timestamps with `chrono::Local::now().format("%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S")`.

### Step 3 — Register the module and its commands

#### 3a. Declare the submodule in `src-tauri/src/api.rs`

Edit [src-tauri/src/api.rs](file:///e:/ruixinglong/tauri-kits/src-tauri/src/api.rs)
to expose shared types and add a `pub mod` declaration:

```rust
// src-tauri/src/api.rs
pub mod product;   // <-- new module

// Shared helpers remain here, reusable by all submodules
pub use self::shared::*;

mod shared {
    use sqlx::{sqlite::SqliteConnectOptions, SqlitePool};
    use tauri::{AppHandle, Manager};

    pub async fn get_db_pool(app_handle: &AppHandle) -> Result<SqlitePool, String> { ... }
}

// Shared response types stay here
#[derive(Debug, Serialize, Deserialize)]
pub struct ApiResponse<T> { ... }

#[derive(Debug, Serialize, Deserialize)]
pub struct PageResponse<T> { ... }
```

> If `api.rs` currently holds an existing module's code (e.g. `user`),
> prefer extracting it into `api/user.rs` at the same time, leaving only
> shared types and the `get_db_pool` helper in `api.rs`.

#### 3b. Wire the handlers in `src-tauri/src/lib.rs`

Update [src-tauri/src/lib.rs](file:///e:/ruixinglong/tauri-kits/src-tauri/src/lib.rs)
and reference each command by its fully-qualified path:

```rust
.invoke_handler(tauri::generate_handler![
    api::api_user_login,
    api::api_user_list,
    // ... existing handlers
    api::product::api_product_init,
    api::product::api_product_list,
    api::product::api_product_get,
    api::product::api_product_create,
    api::product::api_product_update,
    api::product::api_product_delete
])
```

#### 3c. Call the module init from `api_db_init`

In [src-tauri/src/api.rs](file:///e:/ruixinglong/tauri-kits/src-tauri/src/api.rs),
have `api_db_init` delegate to each module's own init command instead of
inlining DDL:

```rust
#[tauri::command]
pub async fn api_db_init(app_handle: AppHandle) -> ApiResponse<String> {
    // Existing user init (or api::user::api_user_init) ...
    // Then delegate to the new module:
    product::api_product_init(app_handle.clone()).await;
    ApiResponse::success("Database initialized".to_string())
}
```

### Step 4 — Create the frontend API file

Each module MUST have its own dedicated API file at
`src/api/<module>.ts`. Never put a module's `invoke()` calls inside
`src/api/request.ts`, `src/api/db.ts`, or any other shared file —
those are reserved for cross-module helpers.

File layout:

```
src/api/
├── request.ts     # generic DB helpers (db_execute, db_page, ...) — shared
├── db.ts          # app-level DB init only
└── <module>.ts    # one file per business module
```

Create [src/api/product.ts](file:///e:/ruixinglong/tauri-kits/src/api/) following
the pattern in [src/api/user.ts](file:///e:/ruixinglong/tauri-kits/src/api/user.ts):

```ts
import { invoke } from '@tauri-apps/api/core'

interface ApiResponse<T> {
  code: number
  message: string
  data: T | null
}

interface PageResponse<T> {
  current: number
  page_size: number
  total: number
  records: T[]
}

export async function pageList(current: number, pageSize: number): Promise<any> {
  const result = await invoke<ApiResponse<PageResponse<any>>>('api_product_list', { page: current, pageSize })
  if (result.code !== 200) throw new Error(result.message)
  const data = result.data
  return {
    current: data?.current || current,
    pageSize: data?.page_size || pageSize,
    total: data?.total || 0,
    records: data?.records || []
  }
}

export async function del(where: any[][]): Promise<any> { /* invoke api_product_delete */ }
export async function edit(id: number, data: any): Promise<any> { /* invoke api_product_update */ }
export async function add(data: any): Promise<any> { /* invoke api_product_create */ }
```

Rules:

- One file per module. The file name matches the Rust module name
  (`product.ts` <-> `api/product.rs`).
- Only this file may call `invoke('api_product_*', ...)`. Page components
  import from here instead of invoking directly.
- Shared `ApiResponse<T>` / `PageResponse<T>` interfaces may be duplicated
  per file (matches the existing `user.ts` style) OR extracted into
  `src/api/types.ts` later — do NOT mix them into `request.ts`.
- The `invoke` argument names must match the Rust parameter names
  (Tauri converts `snake_case` Rust params from `camelCase` JS keys, e.g.
  `page_size` -> `pageSize`). When passing a struct, the JS key must match
  the Rust parameter name exactly (e.g. `{ product: data }` for `product: Product`).

### Step 5 — Create the frontend page

Each module gets its own dedicated directory under `src/components/<module>/`.
All module files (page component, form component, styles) live inside this folder.

Directory layout:

```
src/components/
├── layout/          # shared layout components (header, menu, footer, etc.)
├── chart/           # shared chart components
├── Dashboard.tsx    # shared dashboard page
├── Chart.tsx        # shared chart page
├── Login.tsx        # shared login page
└── product/         # <-- new module directory
    ├── index.tsx    # main page (search + stats + table)
    ├── index.scss   # styles
    └── Form.tsx     # add/edit drawer
```

Create [src/components/product/index.tsx](file:///e:/ruixinglong/tauri-kits/src/components/)
as the main page component, mirroring
[src/components/User.tsx](file:///e:/ruixinglong/tauri-kits/src/components/User.tsx):

```tsx
// src/components/product/index.tsx
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react'
import { Form, Row, Col, Input, Button, Table, Popconfirm, message, Card, Space, Typography, Tag } from 'antd'
import { PlusOutlined, SearchOutlined, ReloadOutlined, EditOutlined, DeleteOutlined } from '@ant-design/icons'
import { useTranslation } from 'react-i18next'
import { pageList, del } from '../../api/product'
import ProductForm from './Form'
import './index.scss'
```

Required in the page:

- `useTranslation()` for all labels.
- A search `<Form>` with a `parseWhere()` helper returning `string[][]`.
- An Ant Design `<Table>` with pagination wired to `pageList`.
- Statistic cards following the `.stats-row` layout.
- A `<Drawer>` form for create/edit, following
  [src/components/user/Form.tsx](file:///e:/ruixinglong/tauri-kits/src/components/user/Form.tsx).

### Step 6 — Create the module store

Each module may have its own state management file at `src/store/<module>.ts`.
This isolates module-specific state from the global `src/store/index.tsx`,
which should only contain app-wide concerns like authentication.

File layout:

```
src/store/
├── index.tsx        # global app state (auth user, theme, etc.)
├── store.ts         # shared context utilities
└── <module>.ts      # one file per business module
```

Create [src/store/product.ts](file:///e:/ruixinglong/tauri-kits/src/store/):

```ts
// src/store/product.ts
import { createContext, useContext, useState, ReactNode, useCallback } from 'react'

interface ProductState {
  selectedIds: number[]
}

interface ProductStoreType {
  state: ProductState
  setSelectedIds: (ids: number[]) => void
  toggleSelect: (id: number) => void
}

const ProductContext = createContext<ProductStoreType | undefined>(undefined)

export function ProductProvider({ children }: { children: ReactNode }) {
  const [selectedIds, setSelectedIds] = useState<number[]>([])

  const toggleSelect = useCallback((id: number) => {
    setSelectedIds(prev =>
      prev.includes(id) ? prev.filter(i => i !== id) : [...prev, id]
    )
  }, [])

  return (
    <ProductContext.Provider value={{ state: { selectedIds }, setSelectedIds, toggleSelect }}>
      {children}
    </ProductContext.Provider>
  )
}

export function useProductStore() {
  const context = useContext(ProductContext)
  if (context === undefined) {
    throw new Error('useProductStore must be used within a ProductProvider')
  }
  return context
}
```

Rules:

- Module stores use React Context, matching the pattern in
  [src/store/index.tsx](file:///e:/ruixinglong/tauri-kits/src/store/index.tsx).
- Each module's store exports its own `<XxxProvider>` and `useXxxStore()` hook.
- Wrap only the module's page component with the provider, not the entire app.
- Global state (auth user, locale) stays in `src/store/index.tsx`.

### Step 7 — Register the route

Edit [src/router/index.tsx](file:///e:/ruixinglong/tauri-kits/src/router/index.tsx)
to register the new module as a child of the protected `/` layout.

1. Add the import at the top of the file (note the directory-based import):

```tsx
import Product from '../components/product'
```

2. Add a new entry to the `children` array of the `/` route (after the existing
   `/user` entry). The `AuthGuard` wrapper already protects all routes under
   `/`, so no extra guard is needed:

```tsx
const router = createBrowserRouter([
  {
    path: '/login',
    element: <Login />
  },
  {
    path: '/',
    element: (
      <AuthGuard>
        <Layout />
      </AuthGuard>
    ),
    children: [
      { path: '/', element: <Navigate to="/dashboard" replace /> },
      { path: '/dashboard', element: <Dashboard /> },
      { path: '/chart', element: <Chart /> },
      { path: '/user', element: <User /> },
      { path: '/product', element: <Product /> }   // <-- new route
    ]
  }
])
```

Rules:

- New modules MUST be nested under the `/` route so they inherit the
  `<Layout>` (sider + header + footer) and the `AuthGuard` protection.
- Public routes (no auth) must be top-level entries, like `/login`.
- Route paths use kebab-case, e.g. `/order-item`.
- Avoid duplicate paths — React Router will warn at runtime.
- After registration, navigate via `<Menu>` (Step 8) or
  `useNavigate()('/product')`.

